[1] At a June 2, 2006 trial in Provincial Court the appellants, Orion Raycraft and Shaunna Raycraft, were found guilty of breaching a bylaw of the Rural Municipality of Vanscoy No. 345. [4] The appellants appeal from their conviction. Four issues are to be addressed:
(1) the appellants’ application to admit new evidence on the appeal;
(2) a constitutional question raised by the appellants;
(3) the significance of the word “hamlet” in the bylaw; and
(4) the meaning of the word “livestock” in the bylaw. Further, the evidence will be admitted on appeal only if it bears upon a decisive or potentially decisive issue in the trial: R. v. Palmer (1979), 1979 CanLII 8 (SCC), [1980] 1 S.C.R. 759; Carriere v. Carriere, 2004 SKCA 80 (CanLII), 249 Sask.R. 240. [15] For the above reasons, the application to admit new evidence on the appeal is dismissed. [17] In any event, the uncertainty on which the appellants rely in attacking the bylaw does not exist, as I discuss in the balance of this decision. The appeal is dismissed.

